# Card Collection Component - Starter Packs Display

## What this demonstrates

A responsive React component that renders a collection of five cards displaying starter pack information. The component features smooth hover animations (scale + brightness with 200ms transitions), maintains visual consistency with the original Brown Hack landing page design, and adapts seamlessly between mobile (vertical stacking) and desktop (horizontal layout) viewports.

## Original implementation

The original implementation was part of a Brown Hack landing page that showcased eight starter pack cards. This extraction reduces the count to five cards and replaces "Brown Hack" with "Columbia Hack" in one of the cards while maintaining all visual design elements including:

- Color theme and typography
- Spacing, borders, and shadow effects
- Hover animations (slight scale increase + brightness)
- Responsive layout patterns

### Key files from source:

Since the source repository structure was not fully available, this implementation is based on the detailed requirements specification. The component recreates the visual design and behavior described in the original Brown Hack landing page:

- **Card Component**  Individual card with image, title, and description
- **Card Collection Container**  Grid layout with responsive breakpoints
- **CSS Modules**  Isolated styling for each component
- **Mock Data**  Hardcoded card content for demonstration

## Dependencies

### NPM packages required

- **next** (v14+)  Next.js framework with App Router support
- **react** (v18+)  React library for component rendering
- **react-dom** (v18+)  React DOM rendering

No additional NPM packages are required. The component uses Next.js built-in `Image` component for optimized image loading.

### Code ported from source

Since the original source was not directly accessible, all code was created based on the requirements specification:

- **Card.tsx**  Functional component for individual cards with hover effects
- **CardCollection.tsx**  Container component managing card grid layout
- **Validation utilities**  Helper functions for validating card data structure

### Mocked in this example

- **Card Data**  `MOCK_CARD_DATA` array in `utils.ts` contains hardcoded information for 5 starter packs:
  - Fetch.AI Starter Pack
  - Columbia Hack (replaced from Brown Hack)
  - Web3 Starter Pack
  - AI/ML Toolkit
  - DevOps Essentials

- **Placeholder Images**  SVG placeholders created for each card icon in `/placeholders/` directory. These are easily replaceable with actual images by updating the `imageSrc` paths in the data.

- **Server Actions**  `actions.ts` includes a mock `fetchCardData()` function that simulates API fetching. In production, this would connect to a real database or API endpoint.

## Component Architecture

### Component Hierarchy

```
CardCollection (main component)
 Card (rendered 5 times)
    Image (Next.js Image component)
    Title (h3 element)
    Description (p element)
```

### Data Model

```typescript
interface CardData {
  title: string;
  description: string;
  imageSrc: string;
  imageAlt?: string;
}
```

### Props Interface

```typescript
interface CardCollectionProps {
  cards: CardData[];
}
```

## Styling Approach

### CSS Modules

Each component has its own CSS Module for isolated styling:

- `Card.module.css`  Individual card styles including hover effects
- `CardCollection.module.css`  Grid layout and responsive breakpoints

### Key Style Features

**Card Styles:**
- Background: `#ffffff`
- Border: `1px solid #e5e7eb`
- Border radius: `12px`
- Shadow: Subtle box-shadow with enhanced effect on hover
- Transition: `all 200ms ease-in-out`

**Hover Effect:**
- Transform: `scale(1.05)`
- Filter: `brightness(1.02)`
- Enhanced box-shadow

**Responsive Breakpoints:**
- Mobile (< 768px): Vertical stack
- Tablet (769px - 1024px): 2-column grid
- Desktop (> 1024px): Horizontal wrap layout

## How to use

### Basic Usage

1. **Navigate to the page:**
   ```
   /app/partner/backwards/prototypes/fetch-model-and-req/created-apps/the-user-requires-a-react-component-that-renders-a/src/app/extracted
   ```

2. **The page will automatically render** with the 5 hardcoded starter pack cards.

### Custom Usage

To use the component with your own data:

```tsx
import CardCollection from './CardCollection';

const myCards = [
  {
    title: 'My Custom Card',
    description: 'Custom description here',
    imageSrc: '/path/to/image.svg',
    imageAlt: 'My image'
  },
  // ... more cards
];

export default function MyPage() {
  return <CardCollection cards={myCards} />;
}
```

### Replacing Placeholder Images

1. Add your images to the `/placeholders/` directory (or any accessible path)
2. Update the `imageSrc` values in `utils.ts` to point to your images:

```typescript
export const MOCK_CARD_DATA: CardData[] = [
  {
    title: 'Your Title',
    description: 'Your description',
    imageSrc: '/your-image-path.png',
    imageAlt: 'Your alt text'
  },
  // ...
];
```

### Server-Side Data Fetching (Future Enhancement)

To fetch card data from an API:

1. Update `actions.ts` with your API endpoint
2. Use the server action in your page:

```tsx
import { fetchCardData } from './actions';
import CardCollection from './CardCollection';

export default async function Page() {
  const cards = await fetchCardData();
  return <CardCollection cards={cards} />;
}
```

## Edge Cases Handled

- **Missing Images:** Image component includes error handling to hide broken images
- **Invalid Card Data:** `validateCardCollection()` filters out cards with missing required fields
- **Empty Card Array:** Component displays "No cards to display" message
- **Responsive Layout:** Smooth transitions between mobile, tablet, and desktop layouts

## File Structure

```
src/app/extracted/
 page.tsx                    # Demo page
 CardCollection.tsx          # Main collection component
 CardCollection.module.css   # Collection styles
 Card.tsx                    # Individual card component
 Card.module.css            # Card styles
 types.ts                   # TypeScript interfaces
 utils.ts                   # Helper functions & mock data
 actions.ts                 # Server actions (optional)
 placeholders/              # SVG placeholder images
    placeholder-fetchai.svg
    placeholder-columbia.svg
    placeholder-web3.svg
    placeholder-aiml.svg
    placeholder-devops.svg
 README.md                  # This file
```

## Customization Tips

### Changing Colors

Update CSS Module files (`Card.module.css`) to change:
- Card background color
- Border colors
- Text colors
- Hover effects

### Adjusting Animations

Modify the transition duration in `Card.module.css`:
```css
transition: all 200ms ease-in-out; /* Change 200ms to your preference */
```

### Modifying Layout

Update responsive breakpoints in `CardCollection.module.css`:
```css
@media (max-width: 768px) { /* Mobile breakpoint */ }
@media (min-width: 769px) and (max-width: 1024px) { /* Tablet */ }
@media (min-width: 1025px) { /* Desktop */ }
```

### Adding More/Fewer Cards

Simply modify the `MOCK_CARD_DATA` array in `utils.ts` to include as many cards as needed. The responsive layout will automatically adjust.

## Performance Considerations

- **Next.js Image Optimization:** Uses `next/image` for automatic image optimization
- **CSS Modules:** Scoped styles prevent global CSS pollution
- **Client Components:** Marked with `'use client'` directive where needed
- **Lightweight Dependencies:** No external UI libraries required

## Browser Support

Works in all modern browsers that support:
- CSS Grid/Flexbox
- CSS Transforms
- CSS Transitions
- ES6+ JavaScript

---

**Note:** This is a demonstration component extracted from a landing page design. For production use, consider adding:
- Loading states
- Error boundaries
- Accessibility improvements (ARIA labels, keyboard navigation)
- Analytics tracking
- Performance monitoring
